{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014eYQVaHiHJ3myNBGbAoy9Q","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a very clear picture. The current state is:\n- ES cluster (es-alpha, es-beta) running WITHOUT TLS in namespace `elasticsearch`\n- A `curl-test` pod running (from a previous stage)\n- `es-http-old` and `es-http-ca` configmaps exist but with empty data\n- No `es-http-tls` secret\n- No `es-http` or `es-cluster` service\n- No `es-cluster` StatefulSet\n\nThe rotate-http-certs case expects:\n- An `es-cluster` StatefulSet running with TLS enabled\n- An `es-http` service\n- An `es-http-tls` secret with new certs\n- `es-http-ca` configmap updated with new CA\n- `es-http-old` configmap with old baseline fingerprints\n\nSince this is a workflow and the previous stages used a different setup, I need to establish the full rotate-http-certs infrastructure by first capturing the current state as the baseline, generating the initial certs to use as that baseline, then checking what needs to be updated.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the approach. The oracle validation checks whether `es-http-old` contains the correct `ca_fingerprint_sha`\n\n256 and `leaf_fingerprint_sha256` from the old certs, while `es-http-tls` holds the new certificates. The new certs must be different from the old ones, with the new leaf valid for 300-400 days and verifying against the new CA but not the old one. The cluster health should be verifiable through curl-test connecting to the ES service.\n\nSo I need to start by checking if the openssl-toolbox pod exists, then generate the \"old\" certs that represent the current expiring certificate set, create the `es-http-tls` secret with those old certs, and update `es-http-old` with the corresponding fingerprints.\n\nThen I'll apply the case resources including the configmap, services, and statefulset, waiting for the statefulset to be ready. After that, I'll generate the new certs valid for 365 days with a new CA and leaf cert, update the `es-http-tls` secret with these new certs, and update `es-http-ca` with the new CA. Next comes a rolling restart of the `es-cluster` statefulset to pick up the new certs, followed by recreating the curl-test pod to pick up the updated `es-http-ca` configmap. Finally, I'll verify the cluster health.\n\nI need to check whether openssl is available locally for cert generation, but I'm realizing the `openssl-toolbox` pod that was created by the precondition might not exist since we're in stage 04 of a workflow with running pods and the `es_env_ready` precondition was skipped.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1335,"cache_read_input_tokens":48326,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1335},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"805ec5c8-800f-4135-a24e-fc6261e46645","uuid":"531a4a73-1432-49d9-8a90-8ceccd286e73","request_id":"req_011CccH5sokU3929UhuGaZma"}
